│ transformed target is more poisonous than the source: the vector reduction    │
│ propagates poison from an unused lane (due to scalar select gating) that the  │
│ scalar code did not use, resulting in a poison result where the source was    │
│ definitively true. The existing code intends to insert a freeze to prevent    │
│ poison from leaking when vectorizing such boolean reductions, but in this     │
│ case it did not insert the freeze.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n- The log    │
│ shows a horizontal reduction is detected and vectorized: \"SLP: Vectorizing   │
│ horizontal reduction at cost:-5. (HorRdx)\".\n- It emits insertelement chain, │
│ vector icmp, and a vector.reduce.or.\n- There is no indication of a freeze    │
│ being emitted. The vector compare has a poison lane (coming from %c), and the │
│ reduction produces poison. In the scalar path, select instructions prevented  │
│ the poison from being demanded (short-circuit-like, poison-safe form), so the │
│ scalar result is defined (true) for the given input.\n- The code has a        │
│ mechanism to insert a freeze to prevent poison leakage from boolean logic: at │
│ lines 19493-19497, it conditionally freezes VectorizedRoot. However, the      │
│ condition includes an extra gate `VL.size() != TrackedVals.size()` which      │
│ restricts freezing in some cases even when safe boolean logic operations are  │
│ present.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe transformation is unsound when the   │
│ input to a horizontal boolean reduction may be poison in lanes that are not   │
│ semantically demanded by the scalar select-based logic. The pass has a        │
│ protective freeze, intended for \"sequential, safe, scalar boolean logic      │
│ operations\", but it is not triggered in this case because of the additional  │
│ predicate `(AnyBoolLogicOp && VL.size() != TrackedVals.size())`. In our       │
│ reproducer, AnyBoolLogicOp is true (there are select-based logical ops), but  │
│ `VL.size() == TrackedVals.size()` so the freeze is not applied. Consequently, │
│ the vector.reduce.or may produce poison, making the target more poisonous     │
│ than the source.\n\nThe bug is that the freeze guard is too restrictive. When │
│ any poison-safe boolean logic operation participates in the reduction, we     │
│ must prevent poison leaking from parallel vectorization. Relying on           │
│ `VL.size() != TrackedVals.size()` to decide whether to freeze misses legal    │
│ cases like this reproducer.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:             │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Location: Around lines     │
│ 19493-19497\n- Change: Relax the freeze condition by removing the `VL.size()  │
│ != TrackedVals.size()` gate. Freeze whenever there is any boolean logic op in │
│ the reduction (or the root is such an op) and the vectorized root may be      │
│ poison.\n\nOld code:\n\n  // To prevent poison from leaking across what used  │
│ to be sequential,\n  // safe, scalar boolean logic operations, the reduction  │
│ operand must be frozen.\n  if ((isBoolLogicOp(RdxRootInst) ||\n               │
│ (AnyBoolLogicOp && VL.size() != TrackedVals.size())) &&\n                     │
│ !isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(VectorizedRoot))\n    VectorizedRoot =             │
│ Builder.CreateFreeze(VectorizedRoot);\n\nNew code:\n\n  // To prevent poison  │
│ from leaking across what used to be sequential,\n  // safe, scalar boolean    │
│ logic operations, the reduction operand must be frozen.\n  if                 │
│ ((isBoolLogicOp(RdxRootInst) || AnyBoolLogicOp) &&\n                          │
│ !isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(VectorizedRoot))\n    VectorizedRoot =             │
│ Builder.CreateFreeze(VectorizedRoot);\n\nRationale:\n- If there are any       │
│ poison-safe boolean logic ops participating in the reduction (select-based    │
│ logical and/or), scalar evaluation may avoid demanding poison values in some  │
│ inputs. Vectorizing into a parallel vector reduction can expose poison from   │
│ unused lanes. Freezing the vectorized root prevents this leak without         │
│ changing semantics for programs where the scalar result may still be poison:  │
│ we only insert freeze when the reduction involves boolean safe logic (the     │
│ intended scope of this protection in the current design). The extra           │
│ `VL.size() != TrackedVals.size()` predicate was an over-conservative          │
│ heuristic that skipped necessary freezes, leading to the shown                │
│ miscompile.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy removing the `VL.size() !=                  │
│ TrackedVals.size()` clause and freezing whenever any boolean logic op is      │
│ involved, we ensure that vectorized boolean reductions do not become more     │
│ poisonous than the original scalar, preserving correctness for cases like the │
│ reproducer. This aligns with the intention described in the comment and       │
│ avoids the Alive2-detected miscompile while keeping the fix localized and     │
│ minimally invasive."})                                                        │
