│ use, resulting in a poison result where the source was definitively true. The │
│ existing code intends to insert a freeze to prevent poison from leaking when  │
│ vectorizing such boolean reductions, but in this case it did not insert the   │
│ freeze.                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:                                                     │
│ - The log shows a horizontal reduction is detected and vectorized: "SLP:      │
│ Vectorizing horizontal reduction at cost:-5. (HorRdx)".                       │
│ - It emits insertelement chain, vector icmp, and a vector.reduce.or.          │
│ - There is no indication of a freeze being emitted. The vector compare has a  │
│ poison lane (coming from %c), and the reduction produces poison. In the       │
│ scalar path, select instructions prevented the poison from being demanded     │
│ (short-circuit-like, poison-safe form), so the scalar result is defined       │
│ (true) for the given input.                                                   │
│ - The code has a mechanism to insert a freeze to prevent poison leakage from  │
│ boolean logic: at lines 19493-19497, it conditionally freezes VectorizedRoot. │
│ However, the condition includes an extra gate `VL.size() !=                   │
│ TrackedVals.size()` which restricts freezing in some cases even when safe     │
│ boolean logic operations are present.                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The transformation is unsound when the input to a horizontal boolean          │
│ reduction may be poison in lanes that are not semantically demanded by the    │
│ scalar select-based logic. The pass has a protective freeze, intended for     │
│ "sequential, safe, scalar boolean logic operations", but it is not triggered  │
│ in this case because of the additional predicate `(AnyBoolLogicOp &&          │
│ VL.size() != TrackedVals.size())`. In our reproducer, AnyBoolLogicOp is true  │
│ (there are select-based logical ops), but `VL.size() == TrackedVals.size()`   │
│ so the freeze is not applied. Consequently, the vector.reduce.or may produce  │
│ poison, making the target more poisonous than the source.                     │
│                                                                               │
│ The bug is that the freeze guard is too restrictive. When any poison-safe     │
│ boolean logic operation participates in the reduction, we must prevent poison │
│ leaking from parallel vectorization. Relying on `VL.size() !=                 │
│ TrackedVals.size()` to decide whether to freeze misses legal cases like this  │
│ reproducer.                                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                       │
│ - Location: Around lines 19493-19497                                          │
│ - Change: Relax the freeze condition by removing the `VL.size() !=            │
│ TrackedVals.size()` gate. Freeze whenever there is any boolean logic op in    │
│ the reduction (or the root is such an op) and the vectorized root may be      │
│ poison.                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Old code:                                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│   // To prevent poison from leaking across what used to be sequential,        │
│   // safe, scalar boolean logic operations, the reduction operand must be     │
│ frozen.                                                                       │
│   if ((isBoolLogicOp(RdxRootInst) ||                                          │
│        (AnyBoolLogicOp && VL.size() != TrackedVals.size())) &&                │
│       !isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(VectorizedRoot))                             │
│     VectorizedRoot = Builder.CreateFreeze(VectorizedRoot);                    │
│                                                                               │
│ New code:                                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│   // To prevent poison from leaking across what used to be sequential,        │
│   // safe, scalar boolean logic operations, the reduction operand must be     │
│ frozen.                                                                       │
│   if ((isBoolLogicOp(RdxRootInst) || AnyBoolLogicOp) &&                       │
│       !isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(VectorizedRoot))                             │
│     VectorizedRoot = Builder.CreateFreeze(VectorizedRoot);                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale:                                                                    │
│ - If there are any poison-safe boolean logic ops participating in the         │
│ reduction (select-based logical and/or), scalar evaluation may avoid          │
│ demanding poison values in some inputs. Vectorizing into a parallel vector    │
│ reduction can expose poison from unused lanes. Freezing the vectorized root   │
│ prevents this leak without changing semantics for programs where the scalar   │
│ result may still be poison: we only insert freeze when the reduction involves │
│ boolean safe logic (the intended scope of this protection in the current      │
│ design). The extra `VL.size() != TrackedVals.size()` predicate was an         │
│ over-conservative heuristic that skipped necessary freezes, leading to the    │
│ shown miscompile.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By removing the `VL.size() != TrackedVals.size()` clause and freezing         │
│ whenever any boolean logic op is involved, we ensure that vectorized boolean  │
│ reductions do not become more poisonous than the original scalar, preserving  │
│ correctness for cases like the reproducer. This aligns with the intention     │
│ described in the comment and avoids the Alive2-detected miscompile while      │
│ keeping the fix localized and minimally invasive.                             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
